\[\bm{\phi}_{i+1}=\bm{\phi}_{i}-\eta\bm{F}^{-1}\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}\mathcal{L}(\bm {\phi}_{i})=\bm{\phi}_{i}-\eta\nabla_{\bm{\lambda}}\mathcal{L}(\bm{\lambda}_{i})\] (20)

_where \(\eta\) is the learning rate and \(\bm{F}\) is the Fisher information matrix (FIM)._

Proof.: The exponential family distribution is defined as the following:

\[P_{\bm{\phi}}(\bm{\theta})=exp(\langle\bm{\phi},\bm{\Omega}(\bm{\theta}) \rangle-Z(\bm{\phi}))\] (21)

According to the expectation of the score function is 0, we can obtain the following

\[\bm{0}=\mathbb{E}_{P_{\bm{\phi}}(\bm{\theta})}\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}\log P_{\bm{ \phi}}(\bm{\theta})=\mathbb{E}_{P_{\bm{\phi}}(\bm{\theta})}[\bm{\Omega}(\bm{ \theta})-\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}Z(\bm{\phi})]=\bm{\lambda}-\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}Z(\bm {\phi})\] (22)

Therefore,

\[\bm{\lambda}=\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}Z(\bm{\phi})\] (23)

where the first equality is due to the fact that the expectation of the score function is zero.

We then derive the Fisher information matrix (FIM) as the following:

